This contract contains the operating system of a fully on-chain asset routing system. It uses fancy (Debruijn) math tricks to     | set up and create a number of tables of binary fields representing assignment to the Trust Channel grouping structure.     | Users are attested to by Trust Anchors, [ Trust Anchors are associated to Trust Channels ], and the relationship of the Trust     | Channels is then additively projected onto the Users own individual mapping.     |     | When routing assets, these mappings are compared, and if there is a match (cheaply done so by the math tricks), then there is     | a return code stating such, and contracts that depend on this function would then send assets.     |     | There is also a rule system in-transit. This radically effects per-transaction cost, but is capable of extreme flexibility,     | as it there are functions from basic asset limit restrictions, to being driven by an external smart contract call with     | arbitrary pass/fail logic.","kind":"dev","methods":{"calculateRelativeTrustLevel(uint32,uint256,address,address,uint256,uint256,bool,bool)":{"details":"| This function generates the relative trust level of the counterparties in relation to all of the Rules set for this Trust Channel. Specifically searches the both the \"active\" directory (which may not be updated given that repeating tasks per-block is not a feature of the ethereum and thus Shyft blockchain), and the \"consented\" channels. Given that users will have benefit to update the blockchain when they are \"active\" and thus set that flag, and the opposite when they may lose their active status, there will be a commonly higher proportion of false positives across active & inactive attestations. Consequently, it is the vendors who have the onus on proving that a customer is inactive.| As Users of Shyft, there is also the option of proving group membership in the Trust Channels, so this Routing function may become the predominant standard.      | This function uses a sliding window 256 bits wide, and narrows down the search to the mutually highest and lowest submap indexes both the sender and receiver have in common.","params":{"_receiverIdentifiedAddress":"the receiver's address","_senderIdentifiedAddress":"the sender's address"},"returns":{"result":"     | NoTrustChannel = no trust channel found      | 0->2**32 - 2 = trust channel found at index"}},"getActiveConsentedTrustChannelRoutePossible(address,address,address)":{"details":"| The function returns whether the first and second addresses have a Trust Channel route configuration that would allow both of them to send over that.","params":{"_firstAddress":"the first address to check for the Trust Channel route comparison.","_secondAddress":"the second address to check for the Trust Channel route comparison.","_trustChannelAddress":"the Trust Channel to perform the route comparison in reference to."},"returns":{"result":"a boolean true/false of whether both the first and second addresses have a specific trust channel route possible"}},"getActiveTrustChannelBitFieldForPair(address,address)":{"details":"| The function returns the lowest trust channel index that the sender and receiver have in common. documentation.text:
@dev | This contract contains the operating system of a fully on-chain asset routing system. It uses fancy (Debruijn) math tricks to
     | set up and create a number of tables of binary fields representing assignment to the Trust Channel grouping structure.
     | Users are attested to by Trust Anchors, [ Trust Anchors are associated to Trust Channels ], and the relationship of the Trust
     | Channels is then additively projected onto the Users own individual mapping.
     |
     | When routing assets, these mappings are compared, and if there is a match (cheaply done so by the math tricks), then there is
     | a return code stating such, and contracts that depend on this function would then send assets.
     |
     | There is also a rule system in-transit. This radically effects per-transaction cost, but is capable of extreme flexibility,
     | as it there are functions from basic asset limit restrictions, to being driven by an external smart contract call with
     | arbitrary pass/fail logic.
@dev simple constant for "no link" to cut down on runtime gas costs.
@dev Maximum number of attestation processing per cycle - this comes into play when performing the cachegraph reconstruction phases.

@dev | Maximum number of trust channel submap compares
     | This is the highest trust channel index (in this case a submap of such, each submap representing 256 trust channels) that can be mapped, based on the lowest submap returned from the trust channel manager.
@dev Mapping for identified address to a specific kyc identity.
@dev The Trust Channel Storage address that this contract is bound to.
@dev The Trust Channel Manager address that this contract is bound to.
@dev The External Trust Channel Prover address that this contract is bound to.
@dev Address for the owner of this contract.
@dev Initializes Trust Channel Manager with the owner set to the calling public address.

It uses fancy (Debruijn) math tricks to     | set up and create a number of tables of binary fields representing assignment to the Trust Channel grouping structure.     | Users are attested to by Trust Anchors, [ Trust Anchors are associated to Trust Channels ], and the relationship of the Trust     | Channels is then additively projected onto the Users own individual mapping.     |     | When routing assets, these mappings are compared, and if there is a match (cheaply done so by the math tricks), then there is     | a return code stating such, and contracts that depend on this function would then send assets.     |     | There is also a rule system in-transit. This radically effects per-transaction cost, but is capable of extreme flexibility,     | as it there are functions from basic asset limit restrictions, to being driven by an external smart contract call with     | arbitrary pass/fail logic.

calculateRelativeTrustLevel(uint32,uint2.details: | This function generates the relative trust level of the counterparties in relation to all of the Rules set for this Trust Channel. This function checks for a Verification Policy, Amount Limits per transaction, and also enables external checks (defined by the Multisig administrators to the Trust Channel) via an other smart contract address.      | Externally referenced smart contracts have the same input/output types as defined in the "getExternalTrustLevel" function.

params._bip32X_type: the token type that is being transmitted
params._foundChannelRulesBitField: the Rules for the Trust Channel this calculation is referencing
params._requiredActive: whether an "active" status is required from the channel
params._requiredConsentFromAllParties: whether "consented" status is required from all parties
params._trustChannelIndex: the Index for the Trust Channel this calculation is referencing

returns.externalTrustLevel: the (external) trust level of the counterparties in respect to the trust channel's routing rules
returns.relativeTrustLevel: the (relative) trust level of the counterparties in respect to the trust channel's routing rules

compileCacheGraph(address,uint16).details: This function initiates the compilation process for a specific _identifiedAddress's attestation (referenced via Index). If this attestation is no longer Approved, there is a mechanism to conditionaly remove the Trust Channel group membership that is associated to the Trust Anchor that initially performed this attestation.

params._identifiedAddress: The end user's smart contract address that attestations are associated to.
params._idx: The attestation (via Index) that will be compiled into the _identifiedAddress's Trust Channel group membership.

constructor.details: Initializes Trust Channel Manager with the owner set to the calling public address.

getActiveConsentedTrustChannelBitFieldFo.details: | The function returns the lowest trust channel index that the sender and receiver have in common. Specifically searches the both the "active" directory (which may not be updated given that repeating tasks per-block is not a feature of the ethereum and thus Shyft blockchain), and the "consented" channels. Given that users will have benefit to update the blockchain when they are "active" and thus set that flag, and the opposite when they may lose their active status, there will be a commonly higher proportion of false positives across active & inactive attestations. Consequently, it is the vendors who have the onus on proving that a customer is inactive.| As Users of Shyft, there is also the option of proving group membership in the Trust Channels, so this Routing function may become the predominant standard.      | This function uses a sliding window 256 bits wide, and narrows down the search to the mutually highest and lowest submap indexes both the sender and receiver have in common.

returns.result: | NoTrustChannel = no trust channel found      | 0->2**32 - 2 = trust channel found at index

getActiveConsentedTrustChannelRoutePossi.details: | The function returns whether the first and second addresses have a Trust Channel route configuration that would allow both of them to send over that.

params._firstAddress: the first address to check for the Trust Channel route comparison.
params._secondAddress: the second address to check for the Trust Channel route comparison.
params._trustChannelAddress: the Trust Channel to perform the route comparison in reference to.

returns.result: a boolean true/false of whether both the first and second addresses have a specific trust channel route possible

getActiveTrustChannelBitFieldForPair(add.details: | The function returns the lowest trust channel index that the sender and receiver have in common. Specifically searches the "active" directory (which may not be updated given that repeating tasks per-block is not a feature of the ethereum and thus Shyft blockchain).      | This function uses a sliding window 256 bits wide, and narrows down the search to the mutually highest and lowest submap indexes both the sender and receiver have in common.

returns.result: | NoTrustChannel = no trust channel found      | 0->2**32 - 2 = trust channel found at index

getActiveTrustChannelRoutePossible(addre.details: | The function returns whether the first and second addresses have a Trust Channel route configuration that would allow both of them to send over that.

params._firstAddress: the first address to check for the Trust Channel route comparison.
params._secondAddress: the second address to check for the Trust Channel route comparison.
params._trustChannelAddress: the Trust Channel to perform the route comparison in reference to.

returns.result: a boolean true/false of whether both the first and second addresses have a specific trust channel route possible

getExternalTrustLevel(uint32,address,add.details: | An internal function to generate the relative trust level of the counterparties in relation to all of the Rules set for this Trust Channel. This function checks for a Verification Policy, Amount Limits per transaction, and also enables external checks (defined by the Multisig administrators to the Trust Channel) via an other smart contract address.      | Externally referenced smart contracts have the same input/output types as defined in the "getExternalTrustLevel" function.

params._bip32X_type: the token type that is being transmitted
params._requiredActive: whether an "active" status is required from the channel
params._requiredConsentFromAllParties: whether "consented" status is required from all parties
params._trustChannelIndex: the Index for the Trust Channel this calculation is referencing

returns.externalTrustLevel: the (external) trust level of the counterparties in respect to the trust channel's routing rules
returns.success: whether the external trust level returns a "success" condition

getKycCanSend(address,address,uint256,ui.details: | An internal function get whether the relative trust level of the counterparties in relation to all of the Rules set for this Trust Channel enables a sending of assets. This function calls getRelativeTrustLevelOnlyClean which will check for external contracts needing to be validated, as specified in the Trust Channel Rules.

params._bip32X_type: the token type that is being transmitted
params._payForDirty: whether the caller of this contract will pay for the "clean" process for one or both of the counterparties
params._requiredConsentFromAllParties: whether "consented" status is required from all parties

returns.result: | 0 = zero kyc detected or error with kyc level | 1 = not enough kyc to transfer | 2 = not enough balance | 3 = can transfer successfully | 4 = won't pay for dirty cache cleaning

getRelativeTrustLevelOnlyClean(address,a.details: | This function gets the relative KYC level on a transactional basis between two counterparties. Included in the checks are the baseline information that is needed to determine counterparty conditions.      | The other method of calling this function include parameters useful in an "Assured Asset" profile.

params._bip32X_type: the token type that is being transmitted
params._requiredActive: whether an "active" status is required from the channel
params._requiredConsentFromAllParties: whether "consented" status is required from all parties

returns.externalTrustLevel: the external trust level of the counterparties
returns.relativeTrustLevel: the relative trust level of the counterparties

getTrustChannelSubIndexFromBitField(uint.details: | This function returns the sub-index (the position within a 256-bit window of the total trust channel bitfield) using the most efficient method of finding the leftmost set bit within N bits - the debruijn search algorithm.      | This function uses a sliding window 32 bits wide (the size of the the debruijn algorithm's search filter) over the 256-bit input bitfield. Further improvements to the debruijn library may result in a 64-bit (or even 256-bit) version of this algorithm. Given gas costs, I believe the cost would be reduced further all the way up to a hypothetical 256-bit version.

params.trustChannelBitField: the 256-bit bit field that the sub-index is retrieved.

proveCacheGraphSegment(address,uint64,by.details: | This function will enable the Shyft Bridge to be used in the proving of off-chain Trust Channel group membership for individuals, allowing for a cross-blockchain integration of the end user's and trust anchor/trust channel group membership.

params._receiptParentNodes: the parent nodes in the path that will be used for the proof
params._receiptPath: the path in the merkle tree that will be used for the proof
params._receiptsRoot: the root in the receipts (like off-chain block headers), the header of this merkle tree that will be proven for a specific value & path
params._rlpCacheGraphProofReceipt: the receipt that will be proven off-chain
params._rlpCacheGraphProofTx: the transaction that will be proven off-chain
params._segmentIndex: the segment in the cache graph that will be updated to reference the group membership of the end-user in relation to the Trust Anchor's (on or off-chain) Trust Channel memberships.

reconstructCacheGraph(address).details: This is a publicly available function that constructs the Cache Graph of the end user. This will call many other internal functions that properly correlate all of the outstanding 'non-dirty' (ie. non updated) attestations, and then create a list of updates and process them sequentially. When this smart contract function call is complete, the associated _identifiedAddress will have been updated with the latest additions/subtractions to the Trust Channel memberships the end user is associated to via attestations.

params._identifiedAddress: The end user's smart contract address that attestations are associated to.

returns.result: | 0: no updates needed    | 1: compilation needs to be complete (more calls to this function are needed to complete the procedure due to gas cost requirements)    | 2: recompiled hash graph

setExternalTrustChannelProverAddress(add.details: Links External Trust Channel Prover to this contract's function flow.

params._externalTrustChannelProverAddress: The smart contract address for the External Trust Channel Prover that should be linked.

returns.result: | 0: not owner    | 1: set external trust channel prover address

params._trustAnchorStorageAddress: The smart contract address for the Trust Anchor Storage that should be linked.

setTrustChannelManagerAddress(address).details: Links Trust Channel Manager to this contract's function flow.

params._trustChannelManagerAddress: The smart contract address for the Trust Channel Manager that should be linked.
